Timeseries plot of Swiss residents

Sara

2022-01-16

Introduction - what was the task?

As part of the Data visualisation and communication course, one of the optional tasks after finishing the first of four sub-courses was to find timeseries data and plot it. A very open question! There is so much timeseries data - the vast majority of at least the academic data I have worked with were timeseries. I need to choose something, so somewhat randomly I choose something I havent worked with before, namely open government data. I want to look at the number of people living in Switzerland - Swiss nationals and foreigners - but additionally show what proportion of the Swiss nationals has/had the right to vote. This could later be compared and contrasted with e.g.the numbers of signatures required for a referendum.

Getting ready

with package imports

library(tidyverse)
library(readxl)
library(scales)

Data sources

all data come from the Swiss Federal Statistical Office

  • Share of Swiss nationals 1951 to 2020
  • Share of non-Swiss nationals living in Switzerland 1951 to 2020
  • share of people allowed to vote {Number of signatures required for a referendum described here}(https://hls-dhs-dss.ch/de/articles/010386/2016-07-18/)

temp_voters <- voters %>%
  filter(year > 1950) %>%
  select(year, right_to_vote)

combo_wide <- pop %>%
  filter(year %in% voters$year) %>%
  select(-total) %>%
  left_join(temp_voters, by = "year") %>%
  mutate(ch_no_right = ch - right_to_vote) %>%
  rename(ch_right = right_to_vote) %>%
  select(-ch)

combo_long <- combo_wide %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c("non_ch", "ch_right", "ch_no_right"),
               names_to = "category",
               values_to = "population") %>%
  mutate(category = fct_relevel(factor(category), c("ch_right", "ch_no_right", "non_ch")))

Calculate some values to be mentioned

# get values to be highlighted below
combo_wide <- combo_wide %>%
  mutate(total = non_ch + ch_right + ch_no_right)

# overall population increase
pop_1951 <- combo_wide %>% filter(year == 1951) %>% pull(total)
pop_2019 <- combo_wide %>% filter(year == 2019) %>% pull(total)
total_increase <- (pop_2019 - pop_1951) / pop_1951 * 100

# ch vs non_ch population increase
pop_ch_1951 <- combo_wide %>% filter(year == 1951) %>% mutate(total_ch = ch_right + ch_no_right) %>% pull(total_ch)
pop_non_ch_1951 <- combo_wide %>% filter(year == 1951) %>% pull(non_ch)
pop_ch_2019 <- combo_wide %>% filter(year == 2019) %>% mutate(total_ch = ch_right + ch_no_right) %>% pull(total_ch)
pop_non_ch_2019 <- combo_wide %>% filter(year == 2019) %>% pull(non_ch)
increase_ch <- (pop_ch_2019 - pop_ch_1951) / pop_ch_1951 * 100
increase_non_ch <- (pop_non_ch_2019 - pop_non_ch_1951) / pop_non_ch_1951 * 100

# status 2019
prop_non_swiss_2019 <- combo_wide %>% filter(year==2019) %>% mutate(prop = non_ch/total) %>% pull(prop)

# women get the right to vote
men_only <- combo_wide %>% filter(year == 1967) %>% pull(ch_right)
right_to_vote_1971 <- combo_wide %>% filter(year == 1971) %>% pull(ch_right)

# change in CH since late seventies
pop_ch_1979 <- combo_wide %>% filter(year == 1979) %>% mutate(total_ch = ch_right + ch_no_right) %>% pull(total_ch)
increase_ch_1979_2019 <- (pop_ch_2019 - pop_ch_1979) / pop_ch_1979 *100

Some Summary points

  • Between 1951 and 2019, the population living in Switzerland increased from 4778900 to 8606033, representing an increase of 80.08% - almost doubled!
  • The increase is more marked for the foreign population (43.84%) than for the Swiss population (606.1%).
  • This means that in 2019, 0.2528% of people living in Switzerland were foreigners - without the right to vote.
  • Another very obvious point is the abrupt increase in the number of people with the right to vote in the beginning of the 1970s - this is of course related to women finally (!) being allowed to vote. With this sweeping change, the number of people allowed to vote more than doubled from 1551909 in 1967 to 3549426 in 1971.
  • Since the women got the right to vote, the proportion of Swiss nationals without the right to vote has decreased. Likely this is related to a change in demographics, with people getting older the younger ones not allowed to vote decrease in proportion.
  • In light of the rather large increase in population, it is interesting to note that both the number of signatures required for an optional initiative (to get everyone to vote on a recent decision by parliament), as well as the number of signatures required for a federal populat initiative (Volksinitiative), have remained stable since the late seventies. In contrast, the number of Swiss citizens in Switzerland has increased by 19.1%. (To give an exact proportion, the Swiss nationals living abroad would have to be included, but I did not find any numbers older than the last 3 years, so cannot quantify their change over time.)

Some extra links not used:

Number of signatures required as comparison

  • 100000 for a federal popular initiative (Volksinitiative, see here); has been 100000 since 1977, 50000 before (historisches Lexikon der Schweiz: Volksinitiative)
  • 50000 for an optional referendum (i.e.getting a vote on something parliament has recently decided, see here); has been 50000 since 1978 (historisches Lexikon der Schweiz: Referendum)
